The frequency of viral load sample collection depends on your stability as a client. Typically, for stable clients, it is recommended to have a viral load test every 3 months. However, for clients who may be facing challenges with medication adherence or experiencing instability, the treatment provider will provide guidance on the appropriate frequency based on your individual circumstances and how well you are adhering to taking your medication.
Viral load refers to the amount of virus present in your body. It is measured in copies per milliliter (cp/ml). A high viral load indicates a significant amount of the virus in your body. This means the results show a value higher than 836 cp/ml. On the other hand, a low detectable viral load (LDL VL) refers to results with a number less than 800 cp/ml. It suggests a lower amount of the virus present.
